TY  - JOUR
T1  - Large Risks, Limited Liability, and Dynamic Moral Hazard
AU  - Biais, Bruno
AU  - Mariotti, Thomas
AU  - Rochet, Jean-Charles
AU  - Villeneuve, Stéphane
Y1  - 2010/01/01
PY  - 2010
DA  - 2010/01/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA7261
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 73
EP  - 118
VL  - 78
IS  - 1
KW  - Principal–agent model
KW  - limited liability
KW  - continuous time
KW  - Poisson risk
KW  - downsizing
KW  - investment
KW  - firm size dynamics
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA7261
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We study a continuous-time principal?agent model in which a risk-neutral agent with limited liability must exert unobservable effort to reduce the likelihood of large but relatively infrequent losses. Firm size can be decreased at no cost or increased subject to adjustment costs. In the optimal contract, investment takes place only if a long enough period of time elapses with no losses occurring. Then, if good performance continues, the agent is paid. As soon as a loss occurs, payments to the agent are suspended, and so is investment if further losses occur. Accumulated bad performance leads to downsizing. We derive explicit formulae for the dynamics of firm size and its asymptotic growth rate, and we provide conditions under which firm size eventually goes to zero or grows without bounds.
ER  - 

